<subSubSection id="C36F6546FEA8FE9B70B5FA0BFBA1FDC5" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BCA36CDFEA8FE9B70B5FA0BFC06FD74" blockId="292.[151,1436,1426,2027]" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70B5FA0BFEB0FFCD" bold="true" box="[151,273,1426,1451]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" reason="1">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
FEMALE. Medium-sized syringophilids (total body length 520–815). 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D4EFEA8FE9B7415FA0AFB67FFCD" box="[1079,1222,1427,1451]" class="Chromadorea" family="Gnathostomatidae" genus="Gnathosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Spirurida" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" phylum="Nematoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7415FA0AFB67FFCD" box="[1079,1222,1427,1451]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">Gnathosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Hypostomal apex with 2 pairs of large and sausage-like median protuberances. Lateral hypostomal teeth absent. Peritremes M-shaped with clearly visible chambers. Movable cheliceral digit dentate, each with 2 minute teeth. Stylophore rounded posteriorly. 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D4EFEA8FE9B70D4FA66FEFFFC71" authorityName="Ausserer" authorityYear="1871" box="[246,350,1535,1559]" class="Arachnida" family="Idiopidae" genus="Idiosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70D4FA66FEFFFC71" box="[246,350,1535,1559]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">Idiosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. All idiosomal setae smooth. Five pairs of propodonotal setae present (
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B74A4F999FB3BFC71" box="[1158,1178,1536,1559]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">vi</emphasis>
—absent), arranged 2– 1–2. Propodonotal shield variable, without pocket-like structures, rectangular in shape, bearing bases of setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B755EF9BDFA34FC5D" box="[1404,1429,1572,1595]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">ve</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70B5F9D1FF0BFC39" box="[151,170,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">si</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B709AF9D1FF6EFC39" box="[184,207,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">se</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7125F9DEFE83FC39" box="[263,290,1607,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">c1</emphasis>
or represented by 3 vertical, sabre-like sclerites, bearing bases of setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7469F9D1FBC5FC39" box="[1099,1124,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">ve</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7450F9D1FB24FC39" box="[1138,1157,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">si</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B74B1F9DEFB0FFC39" box="[1171,1198,1607,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">c1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B74C7F9D1FB5DFC39" box="[1253,1276,1608,1631]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">se</emphasis>
. Hysteronotal shield variable, fused or not to pygidial shield. Setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7325F9F2FC83FCE5" box="[775,802,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d1</emphasis>
situated slightly closer to 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7478F9F2FBD7FCE5" box="[1114,1142,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d2</emphasis>
than to 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B74F9F9F2FB54FCE5" box="[1243,1269,1643,1667]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">e2</emphasis>
or equidistant between bases of setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7182F916FE1DFCC1" box="[416,444,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d2</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B71D7F916FDAEFCC1" box="[501,527,1679,1703]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">e2</emphasis>
. Pseudanal and genital series each with 2 pairs of setae. Aggenital series with 3 pairs of setae. Hysteronotal setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7236F92AFD90FCAD" box="[532,561,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d1</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B721DF92AFDFAFCAD" box="[575,603,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d2</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B72B6F92AFD0FFCAD" box="[660,686,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">e2</emphasis>
long. Terminal setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7386F92AFC18FCAD" box="[932,953,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">f2</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B73D0F92AFBAFFCAD" box="[1010,1038,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">h2</emphasis>
long, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7475F92AFBCDFCAD" box="[1111,1132,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">f1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7487F92AFB60FCAD" box="[1189,1217,1715,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">h1</emphasis>
short. 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7532F92DFAE4FCAD" box="[1296,1349,1716,1739]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">Legs</emphasis>
. Legs I thicker than II–IV. Setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B718DF94EFDA8FC89" box="[431,521,1751,1775]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">dFII–IV</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7262F941FDCBFC89" box="[576,618,1752,1775]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">vsII</emphasis>
absent. Antaxial and paraxial members of claw pair subequal in size and shape, without basal angle. Apodemes I parallel fused to apodemes II.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA36CDFEA8FE9B70E5F886FBA1FDC5" blockId="292.[151,1436,1426,2027]" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">
MALE. Characters as in females except: small mites (total body length 350–600); hypostomal apex smooth; movable cheliceral digit edentate; propodonotal setae arranged 2–2–1. Setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B73CDF8DAFBABFD3D" box="[1007,1034,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d1</emphasis>
situated slightly closer to 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B750DF8DAFAE8FD3D" box="[1327,1353,1859,1883]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">e2</emphasis>
than to 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70B5F8FEFF12FD19" box="[151,179,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d2</emphasis>
or equidistant between bases of setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B724AF8FEFD25FD19" box="[616,644,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d2</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B729FF8FEFD76FD19" box="[701,727,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">e2</emphasis>
; hysteronotal setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B7399F8FEFC76FD19" box="[955,983,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d2</emphasis>
long or short, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B74A2F8FEFB3DFD19" box="[1152,1180,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">d1</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B74F6F8FEFB4EFD19" box="[1236,1263,1895,1919]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">e2</emphasis>
short, terminal setae 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70F4F812FF4AFDC5" box="[214,235,1931,1955]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">f2</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70D8F812FEB7FDC5" box="[250,278,1931,1955]" italics="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">h2</emphasis>
short; aggenital series with 2 pairs of setae; apodemes I divergent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36F6546FEA8FE9A70E5F836FE2DFB71" lastPageId="293" lastPageNumber="294" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BCA36CDFEA8FE9B70E5F836FD16FD8D" blockId="292.[151,1436,1426,2027]" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA8FE9B70E5F836FEF3FDA1" bold="true" box="[199,338,1967,1991]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" reason="1">
<collectingRegion id="49B1F82FFEA8FE9B70E5F836FF5EFDA1" box="[199,255,1967,1991]" country="Afghanistan" name="Khost" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">Host</collectingRegion>
range.
</emphasis>
Mites of this genus are associated with columbiform birds of the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D4EFEA8FE9B74A7F836FAAFFDA1" box="[1157,1294,1967,1991]" class="Aves" family="Columbidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Columbiformes" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Columbidae</taxonomicName>
and falconiform birds of the family 
<taxonomicName id="4C754D4EFEA8FE9B7189F84AFD94FD8D" authorityName="Vigors" authorityYear="1824" box="[427,565,2003,2027]" class="Aves" family="Accipitridae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Accipitriformes" pageId="292" pageNumber="293" phylum="Chordata" rank="family">Accipitridae</taxonomicName>
(
<tableCitation id="C6F70376FEA8FE9B7266F84AFD08FD8D" box="[580,681,2003,2027]" captionStart="TABLE 19" captionStartId="293.[151,231,349,370]" captionText="TABLE 19. Distribution of Peristerophila spp. on hosts" pageId="292" pageNumber="293">Table 19</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA36CDFEA9FE9A70E5FF0EFF56FAB4" blockId="293.[151,1436,151,279]" pageId="293" pageNumber="294">
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA9FE9A70E5FF0EFE8BFAD6" bold="true" box="[199,298,151,176]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="293" pageNumber="294" reason="1">Habitat.</emphasis>
Quills of pimaries, secondaries, tertiaries, primary coverts, secondary coverts, rectrices, and body feathers.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BCA36CDFEA9FE9A70E5FF44FE2DFB71" blockId="293.[151,1436,151,279]" pageId="293" pageNumber="294">
<emphasis id="B901EADFFEA9FE9A70E5FF44FE35FA90" bold="true" box="[199,404,221,246]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="293" pageNumber="294" reason="1">Species included.</emphasis>
This genus comprises 2 species known from the Palaearctic (2 species), Neotropic (1), and Ethiopian (1) regions.
</paragraph>
